.014065880328416824, 0.008013389073312283, -0.002662000712007284, -0.017297526821494102, 0.0471491813659668, -0.0019239253597334027, -0.02824130654335022, -0.013594826683402061, -0.008741878904402256, 0.0012461011065170169, 0.007898364216089249, -0.0038779762107878923, -0.001875998335890472, -0.014657435938715935, 0.005302091594785452, 0.02523970976471901, 0.024560516700148582, 0.01559954322874546, 0.011940660886466503, 0.025546442717313766, -0.02216142974793911, -0.009103384800255299, 0.017549484968185425, 0.0027551159728318453, -0.016497831791639328, -0.004009433090686798, 0.0014022061368450522, -0.01637732982635498, 0.013540052808821201, 0.002352529438212514, 0.030804716050624847, -0.020671585574746132, -0.019619930535554886, -0.011984480544924736, -0.007646405138075352, 0.01358387153595686, 0.023552680388092995, 0.0008065423462539911, 0.012871813960373402, 0.010943780653178692, -0.010357702150940895, -0.016333509236574173, -0.016202053055167198, 0.018962645903229713, -0.0033548877108842134, 0.04763118922710419, 0.0019718522671610117]], "input": ["\"CAUSES OF VARIANCES\":\"Causes of variances can include factors such as buying cheaper materials leading to favorable price variances but adverse usage variances, and other common factors affecting multiple variances.\"", "\"RESPONSIBILITY FOR VARIANCES\":\"Responsibility for variances typically lies with specific departments and managers, such as the purchasing department for materials price variance, human resources or factory manager for labor rate variances, and production manager for material usage variances.\"", "\"MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES\":\"Mix and yield variances are typically controlled by the production manager, who supervises the production process. However, these may also be affected by the quality of materials used, which could be the responsibility of the purchasing manager.\"", "\"OVERHEAD VARIANCES\":\"Overhead variances are the responsibility of the appropriate managers, such as equipment maintenance expenditure depending on the maintenance manager.\"", "\"OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\":\"Operational variances\" are a better reflection of the underlying performance of managers and are calculated using the revised standard. They are generally a more reliable indicator of performance than traditional variances and should be revised if they become outdated or unreasonable.", "\"EXAMPLE OF NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS\":\"A past exam question involved a company that manufactured soup. The production manager kept costs down, reporting large favourable mix and yield variances, but this led to a decline in product quality and customer complaints, ultimately threatening long-term demand and profits.\"", "\"IMPROVING FUTURE PERFORMANCE\":\"After identifying the causes of variances, appropriate actions can be taken to ensure future performance improves, such as including non-financial factors in managers' appraisal systems, regularly reviewing and updating variances, and using target costing to identify ways to reduce costs.\"", "\"RELEVANCE OF VARIANCES IN THE MODERN ENVIRONMENT OF JIT AND TQM\":\"Variance analysis may not be relevant in the modern, rapidly changing business world and can lead to dysfunctional behaviour. JIT and TQM environments emphasize qualitative performance and tailored production, making traditional variance analysis less meaningful.\"", "\"BEHAVIOURAL PROBLEMS IN RAPIDLY CHANGING ENVIRONMENTS\":\"Standard costing and variance analysis can have adverse effects on behaviour in a rapidly changing environment, such as focusing too much on internal standards and not reflecting learning curves associated with new products.\"", "\"SUMMARY OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Actual performance is compared with budgets at the end of each budget period. Standards may be revised before performing variance analysis, and traditional cost variances can be analyzed into planning and operational variances.\"", "\"MATERIAL USAGE VARIANCES\":", "\"STANDARD COSTING AND VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Standard costing and variance analysis aim to improve operational efficiency by comparing actual performance to standard performance and analyzing variances.\"", "\"FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (FPIS)\":\"Financial performance indicators (FPIs) include measures such as profitability, liquidity, efficiency, and gearing. These traditional performance measures focus on financial aspects such as return on capital, profit margins, and liquidity ratios.\"", "\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (NFPIS)\":Non-financial performance indicators (NFPIs) are measures that focus on qualitative aspects of performance, such as product quality, customer satisfaction, and staff morale. These indicators assess aspects of performance that are not directly related to financial metrics and are used to supplement financial measures. By evaluating these qualitative factors, NFPIs provide a more comprehensive understanding of an organization's overall performance.", "\"RETURN ON EQUITY (ROE)\":Return on equity (ROE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability of a company in relation to its equity. It is calculated as Profit after tax divided by the sum of Share capital and reserves, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROE can also be expressed as Profit before or after tax divided by Equity. This ratio provides insight into how effectively a company is using its equity to generate profits.", "\"RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED (ROCE)\":Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability and efficiency of a company's capital investments. It is calculated as the operating profit divided by the sum of equity and long-term liabilities, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROCE can also be expressed as the product of asset turnover and operating profit margin. Another way to calculate ROCE is by dividing profit before interest and tax by capital employed, then multiplying by 100. This metric provides insight into how well a company is generating profits from its capital and is a key indicator of financial performance."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}